Kentucky bluegrass ( amount of forage or feed required to feed one animal unit--one cow, one horse, one mule, five sheep, or five goats--for 30 days).

Grasses include smooth brome, orchard grass, reed canary-grass, and tall fescue (the amount of forage or feed required to feed one animal unit--one cow, one horse, one mule, five sheep, or five goats--for 30 days).
The low range of incline of the surface of a soil.  It is expressed on a percentage scale based on the difference in the number of feet of rise or fall per 100 feet of horizontal distance.
The high range of incline of the surface of a soil.  It is expressed on a percentage scale based on the difference in the number of feet of rise or fall per 100 feet of horizontal distance.
The temporary covering of soil with water from overflowing streams and runoff from adjacent slopes. NONE=0, RARE=10, OCCAS=20, FREQ=40, PONDED=50
The average capacity of soils to hold water available for use by most plants.  It is commonly expressed as inches of water per inch of soil.
Average bulk density of surface: the weight of soil (oven dry) per unit volume
Average bulk density of subsoil: the weight of soil (oven dry) per unit volume
Depth midpoint (0-60) to a discontinuity in texture or composition that is likely to significantly affect rooting volume, penetration of roots, movement of water, or storage of water.

The quality of the soil that enables water to move through the profile.  Permeability is measured as the number of inches per hour that water moves downward through the saturated soil.  0=very rapid, 95 = very slow
The frequency and duration of periods of saturation or partial saturation 10 = excessive, 70 = very poor.
The percent plant and animal residue in the soil in various stages of decomposition
The range of percent plant and animal residue in the soil in various stages of decomposition.
A measure of surface horizon acidity or alkalinity of a soil, expressed as pH.
Indicator of the susceptibility of a soil to sheet and rill erosion by water,
An estimate of the maximum average annual rate of soil erosion by water that can occur without affecting crop productivity over a sustained period.  The rate is in tons per acre per year
The average % content of mineral soil particles <0.002 mm in diameter
The average percentage of total sand in the surface horizon
Thickness of topsoil (the upper part of the soil) which is the most favorable material for plant growth.
